---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
import CompareBody from '../components/CompareBody.astro';
---
<Layout seoSlug="/solid-affiliate-vs-asteris">
  <CompareBody
    rivalName="Solid Affiliate"
    rivalTagline="A WooCommerce-only affiliate plugin focused exclusively on WC stores. Direct, modern, no SaaS layer."
    rivalUrl="https://solidaffiliate.com"
    intro="Solid Affiliate is a WooCommerce-only affiliate plugin that does its core job well and ships per-product commission rates in core — a feature AffiliateWP charges extra for. Asteris Affiliates extends the same self-hosted model with two-tier referrals, EDD + Surecart adapters, AI swipe-copy generator, cloud-assist fraud detection and Stripe Connect Express direct payouts, included from $149/yr."
    whenRivalWins={[
      'You\'re committed exclusively to WooCommerce and want a single-purpose tool',
      'You value Solid Affiliate\'s narrower focus and simpler admin surface',
      'You don\'t need MLM, AI swipe, cloud-fraud, Stripe Connect, EDD or Surecart support and never will',
    ]}
    whenAsterisWins={[
      'EDD + Surecart adapters — Solid Affiliate is WooCommerce-only',
      'Two-tier (MLM) referrals included from Starter',
      'AI swipe-copy generator built in (no Solid Affiliate equivalent)',
      'Cloud-assist fraud detection (opt-in, SHA-256 hashed)',
      'Stripe Connect Express direct payouts at 0.25%',
      'PayPal API auto-batch payouts',
      'Vanity /go/ landing pages with cookie + view tracking',
      'A/B email testing on transactional emails',
      'Real-time stats REST API',
      'Full WP-CLI suite',
    ]}
    comparisonRows={[
      { feature: 'WooCommerce support',          rival: 'Yes (native)',         asteris: 'Yes (native)',           win: 'tie' },
      { feature: 'EDD adapter',                  rival: 'Not available',        asteris: 'Included',               win: 'asteris' },
      { feature: 'Surecart adapter',             rival: 'Not available',        asteris: 'Included',               win: 'asteris' },
      { feature: 'Custom cart adapter API',      rival: 'Not available',        asteris: 'Order_Source interface', win: 'asteris' },
      { feature: 'Two-tier (MLM) referrals',     rival: 'Not available',        asteris: 'Included from Starter',  win: 'asteris' },
      { feature: 'AI swipe-copy generator',      rival: 'Not available',        asteris: 'Included',               win: 'asteris' },
      { feature: 'Per-product commission rates', rival: 'Included',             asteris: 'Included',               win: 'tie' },
      { feature: 'Cloud-assist fraud detection', rival: 'Not available',        asteris: 'Opt-in (hashed)',        win: 'asteris' },
      { feature: 'Stripe Connect direct payouts',rival: 'Not available',        asteris: 'Included',               win: 'asteris' },
      { feature: 'PayPal API auto-batch',        rival: 'Limited',              asteris: 'Included',               win: 'asteris' },
      { feature: 'Vanity /go/ landing pages',    rival: 'Not available',        asteris: 'Included',               win: 'asteris' },
      { feature: 'A/B email testing',            rival: 'Not available',        asteris: 'Included',               win: 'asteris' },
      { feature: 'WP-CLI commands',              rival: 'Limited',              asteris: 'Full suite',             win: 'asteris' },
      { feature: 'Self-hosted',                  rival: 'Yes',                  asteris: 'Yes',                    win: 'tie' },
    ]}
    migrateSlug="/migrate/from-solid-affiliate"
  >
    <section class="prose">
      <div class="prose-inner">
        <h2>Solid Affiliate is the WooCommerce-purist pick — Asteris is the multi-cart pick</h2>
        <p>If you're 100% WooCommerce and you'll never sell anything outside WC, Solid Affiliate is a clean, focused choice. Its per-product commission rate handling is in core (rather than as a paid add-on like AffiliateWP), the admin is tight, and it doesn't try to do anything outside WooCommerce. The trade-off is the size of the feature surface — Solid Affiliate is a small product, and that's deliberate on their side.</p>
        <p>The stores who switch from Solid Affiliate to Asteris tend to fall into three groups: stores adding a second cart (an EDD course site, a Surecart digital store) and discovering Solid Affiliate can't track it; stores wanting to add a two-tier MLM layer to their referral program; and stores wanting Stripe Connect direct payouts at 0.25% rather than manual mark-as-paid or PayPal's 2% mass-pay flow.</p>
        <h3>The EDD or Surecart trigger</h3>
        <p>This is the most common reason stores leave Solid Affiliate. You launch a course site on EDD, or move digital downloads to Surecart, and suddenly you've got two stores and only one of them has affiliate tracking. Asteris's adapters cover both with the same admin and the same affiliate portal — affiliates see one dashboard regardless of which store generated the commission. <a href="/docs/integrations/edd">EDD adapter docs →</a> · <a href="/docs/integrations/surecart">Surecart adapter docs →</a></p>
        <h3>The MLM trigger</h3>
        <p>Solid Affiliate doesn't offer two-tier referrals and we don't see it on their roadmap. If you ever want to add a 5% tier-2 layer (affiliates earn 5% on sub-affiliates they recruit), Asteris ships it in Starter. <a href="/docs/commissions/two-tier">Two-tier docs →</a></p>
        <h3>The payout trigger</h3>
        <p>Manual mark-as-paid works fine when you have 5 affiliates. At 50 affiliates with monthly payouts, it's a job in itself. Asteris ships Stripe Connect Express (0.25% fee, direct to bank), PayPal Payouts API (2% with batch scheduling), and bank-CSV (AU + US formats) in core. <a href="/docs/payouts/stripe-connect">Stripe Connect docs →</a></p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="prose dark">
      <div class="prose-inner">
        <h2>Migrating from Solid Affiliate</h2>
        <p>Solid Affiliate's data export covers affiliates, commissions and historical payouts. Our <a href="/migrate/from-solid-affiliate">Solid Affiliate migration guide</a> walks through the WP-CLI command that reads that export and creates matching records in Asteris. Solid Affiliate's referral parameter keeps working via a compatibility redirect — affiliate links you've already published continue to track and credit the matching Asteris affiliate.</p>

        <h2>The reporting and admin UX comparison</h2>
        <p>Both plugins have clean admin UIs. Solid Affiliate's strength is its single-purpose focus — the admin has fewer screens because there are fewer features, and that's a virtue if you want a minimal cognitive surface. Asteris's admin has more screens because it manages more capabilities — MLM tier-2 ratio settings, AI swipe-copy library, cloud-fraud signal toggles, Stripe Connect onboarding, A/B email variants. Both are well-organised; one is just bigger.</p>
        <p>Where Asteris pulls ahead on admin UX is the cross-cart unified view. If you're running WC + EDD + Surecart on the same WordPress install (which an increasing number of multi-product stores are), Asteris shows one affiliate list, one commission ledger, one payout queue across all three carts. Solid Affiliate shows only the WC side; the EDD and Surecart sides don't exist in its admin because the plugin doesn't track them.</p>
        <p>For reporting depth, both plugins ship the basics: 30-day commission totals, top-affiliate leaderboard, conversion-rate breakdowns. Asteris adds A/B email test results, swipe-copy click-through tracking, fraud-detection alerts, and cloud-assist signal contribution stats. Solid Affiliate's reports cover the WC-attribution core well; the additional Asteris reports are mostly relevant to features Solid Affiliate doesn't ship in the first place.</p>

        <h2>Migration tooling and support</h2>
        <p>Solid Affiliate exports cleanly via Tools → Export, and our importer handles the standard format. The migration itself is among the shortest in our test set — Solid Affiliate's data model is close enough to Asteris's that the import command finishes in under a minute for typical stores. Pro and Agency tiers include hands-on migration support; we'll run the import for you and verify balances against Solid Affiliate's reports before you cut over. See the <a href="/migrate/from-solid-affiliate">Solid Affiliate migration guide</a> for the step-by-step.</p>

        <h2>The honest case for staying on Solid Affiliate</h2>
        <p>Stay on Solid Affiliate if you're WooCommerce-only forever, you don't need MLM, you're happy with manual or PayPal mass-pay payouts, and you actively prefer a small focused product over a fuller-featured one. We respect that preference and we won't try to talk you out of it. For everyone else — particularly the multi-cart and growing-program crowd — <a href="/pricing">Asteris's $149/yr Starter</a> is the lower-friction answer.</p>
      </div>
    </section>
  </CompareBody>
</Layout>

<style>
  .prose { padding: 64px 24px; background: #fff; border-top: 1px solid var(--c-border); }
  .prose.dark { background: var(--c-bg); }
  .prose-inner { max-width: 820px; margin: 0 auto; }
  .prose h2 { font-size: clamp(24px, 3vw, 32px); margin: 36px 0 18px; }
  .prose h2:first-child { margin-top: 0; }
  .prose h3 { font-size: 18px; margin: 24px 0 10px; color: var(--c-mint); }
  .prose p { font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.65; color: var(--c-text); margin-bottom: 14px; }
  .prose a { color: var(--c-mint); font-weight: 600; }
  .prose code { background: rgba(0,0,0,0.06); padding: 1px 5px; border-radius: 3px; font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: 13px; }
  .prose strong { color: var(--c-text); font-weight: 700; }
</style>
